SIMPLE: enrich
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enrich
<hw>En*rich"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Enriched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Enriching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>enrichir</ets>; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) +
<ets>riche</ets> rich. See <er>Rich</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
make rich with any kind of wealth; to render opulent; to increase the
possessions of; <as>as, to <ex>enrich</ex> the understanding with
knowledge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seeing, Lord, your great mercy⟦br⟧
Us hath <qex>enriched</qex> so openly.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer's
Dream.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To supply with ornament; to adorn; <as>as, to
<ex>enrich</ex> a ceiling by frescoes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make rich with manure; to fertilize; -- said of
the soil; <as>as, to <ex>enrich</ex> land by irrigation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To supply with knowledge; to instruct; to store; --
said of the mind.</def> <rj><au>Sir W. Raleigh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enricher</ent>⟦br⟧
